haping Japanese thought (shiso).In addressing the political, historical, and cultural issues that have dominated Japanese society, these essays cross a range of disciplines, including literary theory, philosophy, history, gender studies, and cultural studies. Contributors examine Japan's imperialist and nationalist past as well as representations and remembrances of this history. They also critique recent efforts in Japanese right-wing circles to erase or obscure the more troubling aspects of Japan's colonial enterprise in East Asia. Other essays explore how Japan has viewed itself in regard to the West and the complex influence of Western thought on Japanese intellectual and political life. The volume's groundbreaking essays on issues of gender and the contested place of feminist thought in Japan discuss the similarities between the emotional bullying of women who do not accept traditional gender roles and teasing in schools; how the Japanese have adopted elements of Western orientalism to discredit feminism; and historical constructions of Japanese motherhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJapan -- Civilization -- 1945-. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Central Asia.2bisacsh1 aCalichman, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChizuko, Ueno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKojin, Karatani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsamu, Nishitani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSakai, Naoki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSangjung, Kang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSatoshi, Ukai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTetsuya, Takahashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela